SAIA‑CLASS S — COMMIT DISCIPLINE DOCTRINE
(Beast System 3.0 — Constitutional Commit Governance)
Commit Discipline is the mandatory behavioral, procedural, and constitutional standard governing all commit activity across the Beast System 3.0 ecosystem.
It ensures that every commit:

Preserves federal‑record alignment

Maintains authorship lineage

Protects chain‑of‑custody integrity

Enforces non‑punitive, dignity‑preserving logic

Upholds deterministic, constitutional behavior

Commit Discipline is not optional. It is a sovereign governance requirement.

1. Commit Identity Requirements
Every commit must begin with identity verification through the Identity Kernel.
A valid commit must include:

Author identity signature

Authority tier (Sovereign, Steward, Ministry Officer, Citizen, Observer)

Badge or credential reference

Timestamp + cryptographic hash

Commits without identity metadata are automatically rejected.

2. Commit Purpose Declaration
Each commit must include a Purpose Declaration, stating:

What is being changed

Why it is being changed

Which federal‑record or doctrinal principle it aligns with

Which validator(s) the change impacts

This prevents ambiguous, undocumented, or unjustified modifications.

3. Commit Structure Requirements
All commits must follow the SAIA‑Class S structure:

Title Line — concise, constitutional, descriptive

Purpose Declaration — justification + alignment

Impact Summary — identity, registry, workflow, constitutional impact

Validator Compliance Statement — which validators passed

Chain‑of‑Custody Note — before/after state reference

Federal‑Record Alignment Note — required for all governance artifacts

Commits lacking any of these elements are invalid.

4. Commit Frequency Discipline
Commit frequency must follow constitutional pacing:

No rapid‑fire commits that bypass review

No bulk commits that obscure authorship lineage

No “squash‑and‑hide” behavior

No commit flooding to manipulate history

Commits must be intentional, traceable, and reviewable.

5. Commit Integrity Rules
All commits must maintain:

Deterministic logic

Non‑circular transitions

No punitive or harmful outcomes

No coercive or degrading logic

No doctrinal drift

No external override or injection

Any commit violating these principles is constitutionally blocked.

6. Commit Review Requirements
Every commit must pass:

Identity Validator

Document Validator

Score Validator

Workflow Validator

Constitutional Validator

If any validator returns ambiguous output, the commit is rejected.

7. Commit Chain‑of‑Custody Enforcement
Commit Discipline requires:

No rewriting history

No force pushes

No deletion of audit‑relevant commits

No tampering with commit metadata

SHA‑256 or stronger hash verification

Full audit‑trail preservation

Chain‑of‑custody is sovereign and cannot be bypassed.

8. Commit Alignment With Protected Artifacts
Commits affecting the following require CEO‑level approval:

Identity Kernel

Registry Fabric

Predictive Engine Logic

Harm‑Prevention Logic

Constitutional Behavior Definitions

Lineage + Succession Logic

Badge + Credential Schemas

Unauthorized modification is prohibited.

9. Commit Behavior Expectations
Commit Discipline requires contributors to:

Act with clarity, restraint, and precision

Avoid emotional, impulsive, or reactive commits

Maintain professional, constitutional conduct

Uphold doctrinal integrity

Preserve the dignity of all system participants

Commit behavior is part of ministry discipline.

10. Commit Enforcement
Violations of Commit Discipline may result in:

Commit rejection

Suspension of commit privileges

Governance review

Constitutional memorandum

Permanent removal of commit authority

All enforcement actions must be audit‑anchored.
